-- Foreign Investors Buy Net 9.36 Billion Rupees of Indian Stocks
-- B y   P a r e s h   J a t a k i a
-- 2012-10-09T11:43:19Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-09/foreign-investors-buy-net-9-36-billion-rupees-of-indian-stocks.html
Overseas  investors  bought a net  9.36
billion rupees  of Indian stocks yesterday, raising their
investment in the equities this year to 906.6 billion rupees, or
$17.5 billion, according to the nation’s market regulator.  Foreigners bought 33.2 billion rupees of shares and sold
23.8 billion rupees, the Securities & Exchange Board of India
said on its  website  today. They bought 192.6 billion rupees of
stocks in September.  The benchmark  BSE India Sensitive Index (SENSEX)  has increased 22
percent this year, helped by the biggest overseas equity flows
among 10 Asian markets tracked by Bloomberg. Flows surged to a
record in 2010, making the Sensex the best performer among the
world’s top 10 markets. The largest-ever outflow in 2008 led the
biggest annual slump of 52 percent.  Overseas Funds sold a net 4.02 billion rupees of bonds
yesterday, paring their inflow into debt this year to 262.9
billion rupees, the data  show .  Foreigners have invested 5.35 trillion rupees in stocks and
1.47 trillion rupees in bonds since they were allowed into the
country in 1993.  The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
